## 6. Initiative Entry Form

### Design Principles

- All fields visible simultaneously — no progressive disclosure, no "next" buttons
- Identical form structure across all 3P types (Prioritize, Plant, Progressively Iterate)
- P-type differentiation lives in placeholder text and coaching language — not in form structure
- Form is accessible two ways: full "Add Initiative" button, or inline quick-add (name only)
- Bulk-upload compatible field structure — same 5 fields, same order, always

### The Five Core Fields

| # | Field | Description | Placeholder / Notes |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | Initiative Name | Short, action-oriented label for the initiative | e.g., "Build Financial Dashboard" / "Define ICP v2" / "Implement Weekly Utilization Tracking" |
| 2 | What We Are Addressing | The current-state problem or gap this initiative responds to. Grounded in their audit results. | Prioritize: "What critical gap is this initiative closing?" / Plant: "What foundation are we laying for the future?" / Iterate: "What existing area needs ongoing refinement?" |
| 3 | What Success Looks Like | The definition of done at the initiative level — the finish line for the whole initiative, not individual milestones. Outcome-focused, not activity-focused. | e.g., "Live dashboard showing profitability by client and project type, reviewed monthly" |
| 4 | Sprint Goal Connection | One sentence connecting this initiative to the sprint goal already defined. The accountability thread. | e.g., "This enables our goal of margin visibility before Q2 pricing decisions." Can be a prompted sentence completion or free text. |
| 5 | Known Constraints or Risks | Optional free text. Anything that might slow this down or require outside resources. | Optional — placeholder: "Anything that might slow this down or require outside resources?" |

### Completion Logic

An initiative is considered "complete" when all five fields have content. The system evaluates completion the same way regardless of 3P type — no variation in V1.

- Incomplete initiatives display a subtle visual tag (muted color treatment + small warning indicator)
- Incomplete status never blocks saving or forward progress
- Founders can save with any number of fields filled
- The incomplete tag persists until all five fields have content
- Sprint Lock is the only moment completion becomes a meaningful gate — the system surfaces a review of all incomplete initiatives before the snapshot is created

### Inline Quick-Add vs. Full Entry Form

| Path | Behavior | Use Case |
|---|---|---|
| Quick-Add (Inline) | Plus button or empty typed row at bottom of initiative list within capability card. Type a name (and optional brief description), press enter. Initiative is created immediately and appears in list as incomplete. | Lowest friction entry path |
| Full Entry Form (Modal) | Opened via "Add Initiative" button. Shows all five fields at once. Founder fills what they know, leaves the rest, saves. Initiative created with whatever fields are populated. | Primary path for thoughtful first-pass creation |
| Result | Both pathways create the same initiative record in the same table. The only difference is how many fields are populated on creation. | |

